; Past-tense endings for non-regular verbs and Konjunktiv forms from ich-form:
; flag *Z:
; er/sie/es = ich
; du
 2 add-spell-rule "Z" "[^hßsz]" "" "st" ; Wie wusSte    > wusStest
 2 add-spell-rule "Z" "[^c]h" "" "st" ;     floh    > flohest
 2 add-spell-rule "Z" "[^s]ch" "" "st" ;     wich   > wichst
; CH,D,F,K and T may also have an 'e' before 'st':
 2 add-spell-rule "Z" "[dfkstz]" "" "est" ;     riet    > rietest
; There are verbs which don't have the -chest form below, such as 'brachst'
; or 'rochst'.  Then use 'brachen/WX', which is only slightly less elegant.
 2 add-spell-rule "Z" "ch" "" "est" ;     wusch > wuschest
 2 add-spell-rule "Z" "[au]ß" "" "est" ;     asS    > asSest
 2 add-spell-rule "Z" "ieß" "" "est" ;     liesS    > liesSest
 2 add-spell-rule "Z" "[io]ß" "ß" "ssest" ;     gosS    > gossest

; ihr
 2 add-spell-rule "Z" "[^dt]" "" "t" ;     wüsSte   > wüsStet
 2 add-spell-rule "Z" "[dt]" "" "et" ;     riet > rietet
;   If you insist on all past tense ihr-forms ending in -et,
;   here is how to do it:
;   [ I didn't check if this is 'normal' or not, but it seems somewhat
;     old-fashioned to me.  My Duden (DDR '73) doesn't mention them ]
;2 add-spell-rule "Z" "[^ß]" "" "et" ;     hob  > hobet
;2 add-spell-rule "Z" "ß" "ß" "sset" ;     schosS   > schosset

; wir/sie
 2 add-spell-rule "Z" "e" "" "n" ;     hatte    > hatten
 2 add-spell-rule "Z" "ie" "" "en" ; auch: schrie   > schrieen
 2 add-spell-rule "Z" "[^eß]" "" "en" ;     nahm    > nahmen
 2 add-spell-rule "Z" "[au]ß" "" "en" ;     asS > asSen
 2 add-spell-rule "Z" "ieß" "" "en" ;     liesS > liesSen
 2 add-spell-rule "Z" "[io]ß" "ß" "ssen" ;     gosS > gossen

; flag *O:
;
; Partizip dekliniert: Wie  verarbeiten -> verarbeiteter
;
; This is similar to flag Y,  but will not necessaryly apply
; to all verbs which have regular (Y) past tense form.
;
; The forms to be generated are the same as for the A flag
; (which could be used with a different stem to do the same thing).
;
; flag *Y wil already produce the -e, -en forms.
;
; -tes
